  <body>
    <segment id="1" parent="14" relname="span">Three Cheers for SHANKS</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="1" relname="volitional-cause"> (for it was he who wrote of the dangers of 
believing that philosophy of science can be surgically removed from the 
otherwise healthy body of science)!</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="4" relname="antithesis">

Historians and sociologists are famous for &quot;problematizing&quot; 
internal/external distinctions in standard accounts of science.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="13" relname="span">  But, 
SHANKS is surely right in seeing this &quot;science without the standard 
stories about science&quot; business as itself putting a NEW internal/external 
division into place.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="4" relname="evidence">  I see no reason to presume that science will able 
to get along without some sort of methodological stories about why it is 
worth being pursued.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="11" relname="preparation">

Finally, to take up SHANKS&apos; last point: </segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="10" relname="sequence">Pick your favorite scientist. </segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="10" relname="sequence">  
Try to find the place where that person&apos;s science starts and philosophy of 
science begins. </segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="11" relname="span"> Very hard to do, I should think, even in cases where the 
person is clearly endorsing methodologies (s)he is not following.</segment>
